# Categorical Data

![Definition](data:image/png;base64,) Data that is divided into groups or categories based on qualitative characteristics such as a person's gender, eye color, or level of educational attainment

- Categorical data can also be represented as numerical values
	- "1" for "high school graduate"
	- "0" for "non-high school graduate"
	- Do not have mathematical meaning and are simply *codes that represent the categories of the variable*
- *Nominal data and ordinal data* are two types of categorical data

## Nominal Values

![Definition](data:image/png;base64,) simply name the different attributes or categories constituting a variable and there is no significance to order

- can be thought of as "labels" 
	- cannot be ordered or ranked in a meaningful way
- Examples
	- gender
	- eye color
	- department in the workspace
	- computer components

## Ordinal Values

![Definition](data:image/png;base64,) name the attributes of a variable and unlike nominal values there is a significance to order

- It builds on the naming or labels as seen with nominal values, but the attributes of an ordinal variable can be arranged in some order  (low to high, more to less, etc.)
- ordinal data exact distance cannot be measured
- commonly seen in surveys measuring respondent opinion or satisfaction

# Numerical Data

![Definition](data:image/png;base64,) is measurable and expressed in numbers

- can be carried out by arithmetic operations
- Examples
	- number of employees in various departments in a company
	- addition of departments to get the total number of employees at the company
- Interval data and ratio data are two types of numerical data

## Interval values

![Definition](data:image/png;base64,) can be ranked or ordered and the difference between two values is meaningful

- can be added and subtracted but not multiplied or divided
- does not have an absolute or "true" zero
- Example
	- Temperature can be negative, zero, and positive

## Ratio values

![Definition](data:image/png;base64,) can be ranked and the difference between two values is meaningful

- same as interval values, but does have a true zero
- Example
	- Length can be zero or positive
	- 0 length has a meaning
	- negative length have no meaning

# Discrete Data

![Definition](data:image/png;base64,) can usually be counted in a finite matter, meaning it has an end value, and can only take on distinct / separate values 

- a discrete variable has a complete range of values that are known and exact
- Example
	- number of children in a family is discrete data because you cannot have fractions of children

# Continuous Data

![Definition](data:image/png;base64,) is impossible to count, and its values can be infinite, the maximum value can take on an endless value

- can be divided and reduced to finer levels
- Examples
	- a person's height is a continuous variable
	- In theory can be infinite (there is no limit on possible height)
	- can be broken down to fractions of inches
	- Others examples
		- weight
		- distance
		- age
